added support for traits (experimental)Traits are special templates that define blocks that you can include innother templates.nnLet's take an example:nn{# 'foo' template defines the 'foo' block #}n{% block 'foo' %}nFOOn{% endblock %}nn{# 'main' template defines the 'bar' block and include the 'foo' block from the 'foo' template #}n{% extends 'base' %}nn{% use 'foo' %}nn{% block 'bar' %}nBARn{% endblock %}nnIn the previous example, the 'main' template use the 'foo' one. It means thatnthe 'foo' block defined in the 'foo' template is available as if it werendefined in the 'main' template.nnYou can use as many 'use' statements as you want in a template:nn{% extends 'base' %}nn{% use 'foo' %}n{% use 'bar' %}n{% use 'foobar' %}nnIf two templates define the same block, the latest one wins. The template cannalso overrides any block.nnThe 'use' tag also supports dynamic names:nn{% set foo = 'foo' %}nn{% use foo %}nnThe 'use' tag only imports a template if it does not extend another template,nif it does not define macros, and if the body is empty. But it can 'use' otherntemplates:nn{# 'foo' template #}n{% block 'foo' %}nFOOn{% endblock %}nn{# 'bar' template #}n{% use 'foo' %}nn{% block 'bar' %}nBARn{% endblock %}nn{# 'main' template #}n{% extends 'base' %}nn{% use 'bar' %}nnIn this example, the 'main' template has access to both 'foo' and 'bar'.nnTraits are mainly useful when you consider blocks as reusable functions;nlike we do in Symfony2 forms or if you use Twig for code generation.n
added support for block renaming when importing traits{% use 'TwigBundle:Form:div_layout.html.twig' with text_widget as foo_text_widget %}n

merged branch arnaud-lb/line-numbers (PR #353)Commitsn-------nn5ec1955 added {% line d+ %} directivennDiscussionn----------nnadded {% line d+ %} directivennThis directive allows to change the current line number in the tokenizer.nnThis allows to generate Twig code from some other Twig or partially-Twig script, and still get relevant line numbers in error messages, when the line numbers of the generated Twig script do not match those of the original script.nnFor example in the following script:nnfoon{% line 10 %}nbarn{{ baz }}nn`foo` is on line 1, `bar` is considered to be on line 10 and `{{ baz }}` is considered to be on line 11.nnThis is similar to `# line ...` directives in C.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/06/05 08:51:20 -0700nnI don't quite yet understand it's use cases.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby arnaud-lb at 2011/06/05 09:17:57 -0700nnThe `{% line ... %}` directive is not meant to be used by humans, but rather by generators.nnThe use case is the same as [#line directives in C](http://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/cpp/Line-Control.html): when you generate a C file from a template, you would prefer that the compiler refers to the line number of the template, instead of the line number of the generated file.nnIn my case, I built a [HAML compiler for php](https://github.com/arnaud-lb/MtHaml) which can target Twig as an output language. I use it as a Twig pre-processor so that it translates HAML scripts to Twig scripts on the fly in a custom Twig_Loader.nnSo I have scripts like that:nn%pn testn%div = foo.barnnwhich is compiled like that:nn

n testn

n
n {{ foo.bar }}n
nnIf an error occurs in the execution of {{ foo.bar }}, Twig will throw an error refering to line 5 in the original script, which is wrong. A simple solution to this is the {% line %} directive:nn

n testn

n
n{% line 3 %}n {{ foo.bar }}n
nnNow if an error occures in {{ foo.bar }}, the error will refer to line 3.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/06/05 09:33:26 -0700nnAh, okay, seems reasonable. Though I'm not sure whether it is appropriate to use the comment syntax to accomplish that.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby arnaud-lb at 2011/06/05 10:41:03 -0700nnYou are right, I changed the request to use the block syntax instead.n

merged branch real-chocopanda/ob_fix (PR #379)Commitsn-------nn75748a5 revert accidental mode changen681d2b8 fix nested buffers issue #374nnDiscussionn----------nnfix nested buffers issue #374nnsee #374 for detailsnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2011/07/09 01:02:50 -0700nnYou have inadvertently changed the mode to 0755. Should stay at 0644.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby macolu at 2011/07/09 03:07:42 -0700nnMode change reverted.nnAbout this Windows bug... Are you talking about the zlib issue? When zlib compression is activated, it adds a buffer level that ob_end_clean() can't close. So  ob_get_level() never go below 1.nnhttp://cksource.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=21653nhttp://www.php.net/manual/fr/function.ob-get-level.php#52945nnIn that case, the first ob_get_level() call will always return something greater than 0. So $level var will be > 0. This should avoid infinite loops.n

merged branch nikic/optimizeVariableAccess2 (PR #382)Commitsn-------nn5b91f12 Update testsna5ef326 Use Template->getContext in non-strict mode toonnDiscussionn----------nnUse Template->getContext() when in non-strict mode, toonnAs described in #380 using the current `isset($context['test']) ? $context['test'] : null` approach can cause problems in some cases: The ternary operator always returns by value and thus PHP's copy-on-write concept does not apply. So `$context['test']` needs to be copied in any case, even though a write never happens to it. Basically Twig is copying the values of all variables ever used inside Twig if it operates in non-strict mode. This is problematic when `$context['test']` contains big arrays as the whole array is copied.nnIn this patch I change Twig to use `Template->getContext` when in non-strict mode too and add an `isStrictVariables` check in there.n

About 2x.nnReasoning: It doesn't make sense to propagate the `is_defined_test` flag into deeper levels in non-strict mode, because all getAttr functions and name accesses will just return `null` if it doesn't exist and `null` is just as good as `false`.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/07/02 03:22:53 -0700nnThough, do not merge yet please. Changes behavior concerning methods.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/07/02 13:34:32 -0700nnHm, I really don't know what I was thinking when I wrote my last comment. There shouldn't be any behavior changes introduced by that change (and tests pass).n

merged branch kotas/master (PR #362)Commitsn-------nnf5b9df9 added `if` modifier support to for loop like {% for k in v if k is odd %}nnDiscussionn----------nn[1.2] added `if` modifier support to for loopnnHi.nnI'm one of Twig users who love it so much. :)nnI've made a patch for adding `if` modifier support to `for` loop in Twig.nnExample:n
n{% for n in range(0, 5) if n is odd %}n  {{ n }}n{% endfor %}n
nnOutput:n
n1n3n5n
nnThis idea comes from Python's list comprehensions. (like `[n for n in range(0,6) if n % 2 == 1]`)nnHere is another example.nnBefore:n
n{% set no_items = true %}n{% for item in items %}n  {% if item.available %}n{% set no_items = false %}n{{ item.name }}n  {% endif %}n{% endfor %}n{% if no_items %}n  No items available.n{% endif %}n
nnAfter:n
n{% for item in items if item.available %}n  {{ item.name }}n{% else %}n  No items available.n{% endfor %}n
nnI hope you like it. But If not, just ignore this request. :)nnThanks.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2011/06/24 01:33:33 -0700nnI like it! I will schedule it for inclusion in Twig 1.2. Thanks.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby hhamon at 2011/06/26 16:43:26 -0700nn+1nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/06/27 00:42:14 -0700nnI think the idea per se is interesting. But I just checked all Twig templates in my whole codebase and couldn't find any use for it. What was your practical use for this feature @kotas?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby kotas at 2011/06/27 01:52:48 -0700nn@nikic My practical use is shown as the second example in the body of this pull request.nnSometimes you need to filter an array by seeing its element's property like item.available or by some condition like item.price >= 500.nnTo do this, in the current version of Twig, you have to write for and if as nested scopes. And if you want to write {% else %} of the for loop, you have to make a temporary variable to see if all elements are skipped.nnI think this feature is not essential, but makes templates clean.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/06/27 06:23:24 -0700nnThe thing about `else` seems plausible. +1nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby chucktrukk at 2011/08/02 17:39:16 -0700nnAlso +1. that makes some very clean template code.n

merged branch jturmel/master (PR #403)Commitsn-------nnc2c01de Add bitwise operators to corennDiscussionn----------nnAdded bitwise operators (and, xor, or) to corenn* Added bitwise operators (and, xor, or) to corenn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/08/02 21:02:14 -0700nnI'm not sure bitwise ops really belong into a templateing language...nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby jturmel at 2011/08/02 21:06:02 -0700nnThat's a general statement to make without knowing why it was implemented at all... no one is forced to use them, however when you do need them, them not being available makes you have relegate something that should be in the view in the particular case I needed them, to be done in a controller instead, which would be quite a bit nastier in my case.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/08/02 23:23:30 -0700nn@jturmel: I do not doubt that there are some cases where bitwise operations are useful. I can't think of one of the top of my head, though I imagine that it could be useful when using bitwise right management or something like that. What I was trying to say is, that I don't really believe that there are enough significant use cases for bitwise ops to justify adding them to the core (I know, You Don't Have To Use It!, but it isn't good to clutter the core with features nearly no one uses). Maybe you could give an example of what you needed them for?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby jturmel at 2011/08/02 23:41:36 -0700nnIt would be one thing if I was implementing some operator that didn't normally exist in PHP itself, but it seems a bit odd to even say that it's cluttering it up, it's 3 lines of code that add 3 missing standard operators from PHP.nnSimply put, I have an object that gets passed to the template that has many properties, these properties are bit values, I need to do checks on them to select/deselect various checkboxes in a grid... this is the cleanest way to do it without mudding up controller code with view logic.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby jalliot at 2011/08/03 01:42:56 -0700nnWhy not adding ``<<`` and ``>>`` then @jturmel?nI don't have a particular use case but I think that if Twig includes those 3 operators, it should also support these 2 to be complete. What do you think?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby jturmel at 2011/08/03 06:07:46 -0700nnOf course, if you guys think we need the shifting operators as well, we can... but modifying data in the view seems much less practical than the one's I added, although I did miss NOT.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby jalliot at 2011/08/03 06:16:38 -0700nnI forgot about ``~`` but sure it should be included as well.nAs for ``<<`` and ``>>``, they could also be used for verifying grant access for example in some implementations.n``{% if some_var << some_other_var & 1 %}``n

merged branch shvchk/patch-2 (PR #522)Commitsn-------nn5f30db0 !empty($date[0]) u00e2u0086u0092 !empty($date)n0182dbc indentation fixnc7a06cb php warning fixna4a2d6f Support of negative timestampsnnDiscussionn----------nnSupport of negative timestampsnnDate could be checked against this condition, as proposed in my patch:nn```phpnctype_digit((string) $date)n|| (('-' === $date[0])n&& (ctype_digit(substr($date, 1))))n```nor this:nn```phpnpreg_match('/^-?d+/', $date)n```nSecond is maybe more readable, but 20% slower.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/11/20 01:59:16 -0800nnCouldn't we do an int validation here? I.e. `if (false !== filter_var($date, FILTER_VALIDATE_INT)) { ... }`. That will allow both positive and negative integers in the allowed integer range. Note though that it will no longer allow ints starting with a zero (apart from zero itself). To support that one would need to pass the ALLOW_OCTAL flag.nnSome tests: http://codepad.viper-7.com/w0MDTHnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby damianb at 2011/11/20 07:50:39 -0800nn@nikic why not `ctype_digit`?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/11/20 07:53:26 -0800nn@damianb ctype_digit is what this PR wants to replace, because it does not allow negative numbers. merged branch arnaud-lb/str-interpolation (PR #515)Commitsn-------nnd41d10c simplificationn2dbb420 moved hard-coded regexesn61986c1 shortcut for non-interpolated double quoted stringsn062ed5c regex optimizationn0e63abb integration tests for interpolated stringsn773fff5 parser tests for interpolated stringsn098634e parser support for interpolated stringsnc8bba24 lexer tests for interpolated stringsna203686 lexer support for interpolated stringsn0bd63dd stack lexer statesnnDiscussionn----------nnString interpolation syntaxnnThis adds support for string interpolation:nn```n{{ foo #{ any expression here } bar }}n```nnI find string interpolation to be often more readable than concatenation, and doesn't have the precedence ambiguity of the concatenation operator:nn```nInterpolation:nn{{ foo #{bar} baz }}n{{ foo #{1+2} baz }}n{{ foo #{1+2} baz|escape }}nnConcatenation:nn{{ foo ~bar~ baz }}n{{ foo ~(1+2)~ baz }} extra parenthesesn{{ (foo ~(1+2)~ baz)|escape }} more extra parenthesesn```nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/11/12 12:41:54 -0800nnReally nice idea. We should discuss the exact syntax though :) Dart for example uses `${expr}` for interpolation or `$name` if the expression is just a name. I think it makes sense to have a special short syntax for the name case, because it is the most common one.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2011/11/12 13:06:51 -0800nn@nikic could you comment on the PR instead of commenting on each commit individually ? it would make it easier to see what is concerned in the PR.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby arnaud-lb at 2011/11/12 14:22:14 -0800nn@nikic Thanks for your review, I'll take care of your remarks.nnFor the syntax, I have no preference. I've taken this one because it has the same semantics. In Ruby and Coffeescript the `#{...}` allows any expression between the brackets. In PHP the expression in the `${...}` must start with a variable name. As you mentioned Dart's `${...}` seems to allow any expression.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/11/12 15:03:48 -0800nn@arnaud-lb If Ruby and Coffeescript use this, the #{...} syntax should be okay. Especially as ${...} might be confusing for PHP developers as it has the semantics of variable variables in PHP.nn@stof Thanks, will do so next time.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby damianb at 2011/11/12 15:38:31 -0800nn@stof he doesn't need to - this is something github handles already. in the PR view, beside the @nikic commented bits, there's a set of links that shows where exactly the comment was in the format of commit sha, filename, and line inside the diff.nnYou can see for yourself right here, upper left:n![pr snapshot](http://i42.tinypic.com/zl6s82.png)nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2011/11/13 01:20:38 -0800nn@damianb The comment appears, but not the context in which the comment was. We have to follow each link to see it whereas comments done on the PR appear directly with their context. This is why I said it is easier when comments are on the PR.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/12/02 15:13:30 -0800nnSo what about this now?nnBtw, `REGEX_STRING` and `REGEX_DQ_STRING_PART` still are hardcoded and do not depend on the specified `interpolation` tags. But this looks hard to change, at least the regexes are quite complicated.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby arnaud-lb at 2011/12/02 15:22:45 -0800nnI think I've addressed all issues (except hardcoding of `#{` and `}` in `REGEX_STRING` and `REGEX_DQ_STRING_PART`.)nnCan this be merged after v1.4 is release if the syntax is accepted ?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby nikic at 2011/12/03 01:53:41 -0800nnThis would be my go for `STRING` and `DQ_STRING_PART` (isn't tested):nn```phpn<?phpn$interpolChar = preg_quote(substr($options['interpolation'][0], 0, 1), '/');n$interpolPart = '[^' . $interpolChar . ']*';nif (strlen($options['interpolation'][0]) > 1) {n$interpolRest = preg_quote(substr($options['interpolation'][0], 1), '/');n$interpolRegex = $interpolPart . '(?:(?:.|' . $interpolChar . '(?!' . $interpolRest . '))' . $interpolPart . ')*';nn} else {n$interpolRegex =  $interpolPart . '(?:.' . $interpolPart . ')*';n}n$this->options['dq_string_part_regex'] = '/' . $interpolRegex . '/As';n$this->options['string_regex'] = '/' . $interpolRegex . '|'([^']*(?:.[^']*)*)'/As';n```nnIt should allow both a single char interpolation syntax (like `{`) and multichar ones (like `#{`).nnBy the way, could we maybe move the compiled regexes out of `$this->options` into `$this->regexes`?n

merged branch Seldaek/globals_fix (PR #600)Commitsn-------nn43ebae1 Reset parsers, visitors, filters, tests, functions when a new one or new extension is addedn3db62da Reset globals when a new global is addednnDiscussionn----------nnReset globals when a new global is addednnif getGlobals() is called before adding a new global, it is never taken into accountnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-01-16T14:27:02ZnnIs it related to #594?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Seldaek at 2012-01-16T14:30:08ZnnSeems like it yes. merged branch Seldaek/inception (PR #610)Commitsn-------nn0d656f5 Add commentsn0255764 Updated CHANGELOGnb327a48 Protect the Parser against recursive parsing issuesnnDiscussionn----------nnMake the parser Inception-ProofnnSpent half a day debugging before I realized what happened, but I'll try to keep a long story short:nnWhen the cache is empty, and the first template containing an assetic `{% javascripts %}` or similar tag is parsed, it will build up the assetic assets or recipes cache, this in turn will tokenize and parse all your templates to find assetic tags and cache that information.nnAt this point the parser is parsing something else in the middle of a parse() call, and since there is a single instance in the environment, it means all the instance vars are messed up and contain incorrect references to the latest TokenStream that was parsed by assetic, etc.nnThis had two effects on my application, both appearing seemingly randomly because it highly depends on the order of things, the state of your cache and probably other factors:nn- The first thing that happened is that a template was compiled using the wrong template filename, which means I had a `__TwigTemplate_abcd` in the file named `dcba.php`, and it would never find the right class.n- The second issue (could not reproduce but I assume it was caused by this as well) is that the parse tree is completely broken and you end up with a parse error because it thinks it's at the end when it's not, or similar problem.nnThe proposed fix basically pushes/pops all the vars into a stack whenever the parser starts/stops, which worked very effectively here and does not introduce much breakage or complexity.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-01-24T17:28:06Znn@Seldaek are you able to create a reproducible testcase for this (which should be failing before this fix) ? It would avoid further regressionsnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Seldaek at 2012-01-24T17:45:37ZnnI'll try to improve on this according to feedback tomorrow. I saw this enough for today :)nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-01-24T17:45:49ZnnI'm writing some unit testsnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Seldaek at 2012-01-24T17:47:02ZnnOk then I'll add @dzuelke's comments real quick.n

merged branch fabpot/named-paths (PR #772)Commitsn-------nn7e5acd1 fixed some possible warningsnf0d0d6d fixed typonb7076fe added Twig_Loader_Filesystem::getNamespaces()n8f7ccd1 moved an exceptionn9426072 tweaked documentationnb9afa84 renamed the default filesystem namespace to __main__nc34541d changed notation of namespaced templates to @namespace/template_pathn0eb4d01 added namespaced templates support in Twig_Loader_Filesystemnc24ea1b added Twig_Loader_Filesystem::prependPath()nnDiscussionn----------nnadded namespaced templates support in Twig_Loader_FilesystemnnEverything is explained in the updated documentation.nnBasically, it gives more flexibility when it comes to manage many templates that are not necessarily related (think frontent vs backend for instance, or templates from different Symfony bundles, ...). It is useful if, for each namespace, you need to look for templates in different directories. This implementation would probably be enough to replace the current Symfony bundle template paths, with more flexibility and less restrictions.nnFeedback is more than welcome. One thing I'm not sure about is the `#` separator between the namespace and the template path. Is it the best choice? We need a character that is not used in filesystem paths, so good candidates are: `@`, `!`, `%`, `$`, `*`, `;`, `?`.nnSome immediate benefits: give the same template flexibility that we have in Symfony to other frameworks using Twig like Silex. Another benefit would be the ability to share template between Symfony and other frameworks like Twig (more on a proof of concept later).nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby alessandro1997 at 2012-07-14T16:25:42ZnnThis is very nice, and I think # is a great choice for the separator character. So they had something like:nn{% extends cms://Home/weather/...  ... %}nIf we could make the cms part a configurable setting then one could use it to point to a custom folder or even to a content provider (symfony cmf?)nnMaybe that would be another approach?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-07-14T16:33:21ZnnThe other syntax possibility is something more like we have in Symfony: `@namespace/template_path`.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-07-14T16:34:37Znn@inspiran: that's another possibility: use the PHP stream notation.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby mvrhov at 2012-07-14T16:36:18ZnnI'd also prefer uri/php streams syntax...nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Tobion at 2012-07-14T16:41:16ZnnOn Windows I can create a file with `#` in it. How does it distinguish that? I don't think we will find a single seperation character that works on all file systems, do we? And `@` (e.g. namespace@file) would be semantically strange (unless you read it from right-to-left).nSo I'd also prefer uri/php stream syntax.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Symfomany at 2012-07-14T16:43:17Znn@fabpot  Pointer Syntax? or greater than character?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby markstory at 2012-07-14T16:43:48ZnnI'm in favour of the `foo://` style syntax.  It is similar to other parts of PHP, and avoids overlap with filesystem characters, and doesn't introduce new unique syntax.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-07-14T16:44:25Znn@fabpot ``@namespace/template_path`` would make it confusing in Symfony. Because locating a resource with the kernel would use ``@AcmeDemoBundle/Resources/views/layout.html.twig`` whereas Twig would find the same file as ```@AcmeDemoBundle/layout.html.twig``.nnAnd none of ``#``, ``@``, ``!``, ``%``, ``$`` or ``;`` is forbidden in filenames on Windows.nnSo I think the URI/stream notation is finenn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby maryo at 2012-07-14T16:46:44ZnnOn Windows @!%$; are valid. Even stretched to the limits of its definition you wouldn't be able to define different namespaces as different protocols (same protocol, different location).n* `@namespace/file/path` - kind of like this one, the `@` signifies that it is followed by a special symbol (being the namespace name) and other than that a normal path.n* Another option we've used in Fuel is the double colon `::` as in `namespace::file/path` (like the `#` it signifies membership, but doesn't have another significance in Twig)nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby gunnarlium at 2012-07-14T17:10:15ZnnDoes it matter what symbols are valid in filenames? I find it more consistent.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-07-14T19:50:31ZnnOne problem with PHP streams is that it makes using template names quite ugly and verbose:nn{% include 'twig://namespace/index.html' %}nnAnd for non-namespaced templates:nn{% include 'twig:///index.html' %}nnfor which we can provide a shortcut:nn{% include 'index.html' %}nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-07-14T19:54:35ZnnIf we are using `@` like in Symfony, it will be:nn{% include '@namespace/index.html' %}nnAnd for non-namespaced templates:nn{% include 'index.html' %}nnAnd for Symfony users, the notation would be the same as for resources. merged branch jmikola/patch-1 (PR #845)This PR was merged into the master branch.nnCommitsn-------nna6a1ef0 Avoid setting timezones on DateIntervalsnnDiscussionn----------nnAvoid setting timezones on DateIntervalsnnEdit: originally, I opened this to ensure the default Twig timezone was always set on incoming DateTime objects, but I came to realize why that behavior would be undesirable. The idea was prompted by this line from: http://twig.sensiolabs.org/doc/filters/date.htmlnn> The default timezone can also be set globally by calling `setTimezone()`.nnAnyway, I did notice an edge case where the code might call `DateInterval::setTimezone()`, so this PR attempts to correct that. Additionally, I added some tests for passing a DateTimeZone object to the `date` filter.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby jmikola at 2012-09-22T17:18:56Znn@fabpot: One question came up as I was looking through this a second time: if `twig_date_converter()` receives a DateTime argument, it will override its timezone regardless of the logic path within (either from the `$timezone` argument, Twig default, or the system default).nnAt first, I thought that it was redundant for `twig_date_format_filter()` not to utilize `twig_date_converter()`, but it looks like that was a careful decision; otherwise, there'd be no way to display DateTimes with their internal timezone. This PR would remove that functionality, so I need to reconsider.nnHaving said that, there does appear to be a bug in `twig_date_format_filter()` in that it could end up calling a nonexistent `setTimezone()` method on a DateInterval object. Would it be preferable to throw an exception or simply ignore the `$timezone` argument if the `$date` argument is a DateInterval?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-10-30T08:56:31ZnnI don't know if not changing the timezone on DateTime object was a conscious/careful decision or not. The documentation is not so clear about that, and there is even a bug report about this behavior: #778.nnFor consistency, I think we can always set the timezone and allow disabling that by passing `false` for the timezone.nnDoes it sounds good?n

merged branch fabpot/template_from_string (PR #874)This PR was merged into the master branch.nnCommitsn-------nn4599188 added the template_from_string functionnnDiscussionn----------nnadded the template_from_string functionnnOne of the most often asked question is how someone can evaluate a template string from a template.nnThe template_from_string function solves this problem (more in the included docs).nnI have two questions before merging this:nn * What about the name? I find it quite long but also readable (`{% include template_from_string(template) %}`).nn * Does it belongs to Twig core?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby boutell at 2012-10-28T16:45:08ZnnInteresting. What are the use cases? Would it cache in some way, the md5 of the string maybe, to avoid having this be a major performance hit on every use?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby gcoguiec at 2012-10-28T16:46:04ZnnAnd what about include_from_string ?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby lsmith77 at 2012-10-28T16:46:35ZnnHeh, was just going to ask the same thing, would a use case be loading a twig snippet from a database? something like https://github.com/symfony-cmf/ContentBundle/issues/8 ..nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-10-28T16:48:09Znn@gcoguiec It is not including anything but creating a Twig_Template instance. ``{% extends include_from_string(foo) %}`` would be very ugly.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby gruzilla at 2012-10-28T16:48:37Znni'd say yes.nim not like the core must can do everything. but besides that, what are the reasons against it?ni can already think of some usecases: user defined dynamic templates, ...nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby alexandresalome at 2012-10-28T16:49:34ZnnIMHO it's a mistake to put it in Twig. People won't get how to use it. My reasons are also regarding cache: will the template be regenerated on each call?nnLooks magicnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-10-28T16:50:06Znn@fabpot I'm not really sure this should be in the core.nBut FYI, there is a [PR on your Twig-extensions repository](https://github.com/fabpot/Twig-extensions/pull/68) adding an ``eval`` function with the same goal (but an incomplete implementation)nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-10-28T16:51:00ZnnThe template is loaded like any other ones, so it is using the cache if you have configured it. No magic included!nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-10-28T16:52:44Znn@lsmith77 yes, that's the main use case.nnYou can also have a look at this thread on the mailing-list: https://groups.google.com/group/twig-devs/browse_thread/thread/a8b7bbae31cade18nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-10-28T16:54:28ZnnI forgot to say that we can also move this function into its own extension, so that enabling it would have to come from a conscious choice from the developer (like the debug function in the debug extension).nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby lsmith77 at 2012-10-28T16:55:32ZnnOK great. Looks like something the CMF will need then. But it would also work for us if its part of the twig extension repo. we could of course also just drop the code into https://github.com/symfony-cmf/CoreBundle/blob/master/Twig/TwigExtension.phpnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-10-28T16:56:59ZnnI have proposed it for inclusion in Twig core (but not necessarily in the core extension) as it seems to be something many developers want to do in their code (mainly people writing a CMS in top of Twig).nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby dlsniper at 2012-10-28T17:05:45ZnnHinn- why not name it `template_string` or `string_template`? Then it would read like: ` {% include template_string(template) %} ` or ` {% include string_template(template) %} `nn- imo this shouldn't be in the core but rather in the extensions part of Twig as you just extend existing Twig functionality :)nnCheers.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-10-28T17:37:12ZnnI've moved the function to a new extension that should be enabled explicitely.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby EvanK at 2012-10-28T18:05:57ZnnI would love to see this as a built-in feature to Twig, as my coworkers & I have had to implement a workaround for something similar.nn(Our workaround involved writing said string to a file named after an md5 of the string's content, and then calling render() on said file, all within the php userspace. It was less than elegant, but functional.)nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Crell at 2012-10-28T19:11:34ZnnThis would lend itself to some of the wacky stuff Drupal has been discussing, too.  +1 on the feature.  No opinion on the name.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby jorgelbg at 2012-10-28T20:45:37Znn+1 for built-in support i think this is something Twig should do out of the box, regarding the name I guess that I'll vote for this name ```{% include from_string(template) %}``` The only thing that you can include is a template righ? So why put this explicitly in the function's name?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby pylebecq at 2012-10-29T09:53:05Znn+1 for me. And for the name, it seems I'm the only one but I would have vote for `eval` :smiling_imp:nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby sstok at 2012-10-29T10:14:25Znneval is bad name as can be confused with eval() in PHP, aka that what is passed is treated as PHP (similar to embeded PHP in Smarty). So this PR is not inventing dynamic inheritance but providing a helper to make it easier. Am I right?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-10-30T12:45:08Znn@acasademont no. It is provinding a way to evaluate a string stored somewhere (in a database for instance) as a template. It is not about making dynamic inheritance easier.nIf your template can be loaded by your loader (for instance a file when using the Twig_Loader_Filesystem), you can use the template name in your variable for the dynamic inheritance. You are not required to build the Twig_Template instance yourselfnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-10-30T12:53:02ZnnWhen you have `{% extends some_var %}`, `some_var` must be the template name. Using `{% extends template_from_string(some_var) %}` means that `some_var` contains the parent template code.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby acasademont at 2012-10-30T13:15:37ZnnPerfectly understood, thanks!n

merged branch char101/fix-debug-lineno (PR #894)This PR was squashed before being merged into the master branch (closes #894).nnCommitsn-------nn7c5854b Fix twig error lineno off by 2nnDiscussionn----------nnFix twig error lineno off by 2nnIt seems to me that the lineno reported by Twig_Error is off by 2 from the real lineno in the generated PHP sourcennFor example:nn```n{% if true %}nYesn{% endif %}n```nn```phpn<?phpnn/*  */nclass __TwigTemplate_d41d8cd98f00b204e9800998ecf8427e extends Twig_Templaten{npublic function __construct(Twig_Environment $env)n{nparent::__construct($env);nn$this->parent = false;nn$this->blocks = array(n);n}nnprotected function doDisplay(array $context, array $blocks = array())n{n// line 1nif (true) { // <- this is line 19n// line 2necho Yes // <- this is line 21n;n}n}nnpublic function getTemplateName()n{nreturn null;n}nnpublic function isTraitable()n{nreturn false;n}nnpublic function getDebugInfo()n{nreturn array (  19 => 2,  17 => 1,); // <- should be return array (  21 => 2,  19 => 1,);n}n}n```nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby char101 at 2012-11-08T08:23:57ZnnSince `$compiler->addDebugInfo()` is called first before writing the node content, usually the number of lines in the PHP code is less than 2 (1 for the // lineno comment, and 1 for the generated content) than the line where the node content is written.n

merged branch fabpot/named-arguments (PR #901)This PR was merged into the master branch.nnCommitsn-------nn4647913 added the ability to set default values for macro arguments (closes #447)na59dcde added support for named arguments for filters, tests, and functionsn65637b7 refactored the code handling arguments for PHP callbacks when compiling nodesnnDiscussionn----------nnNamed arguments and macro default valuesnnThis PR contains two new features. Even if they are not related, the code needed to make them work was almost the same.nnThe first feature is the ability to use named arguments for functions, tests, and filters:nn```jinjan{{ data|convert_encoding('UTF-8', 'iso-2022-jp') }}nn{# versus #}nn{{ data|convert_encoding(from='iso-2022-jp', to='UTF-8') }}n```nnThe syntax is borrowed from Python where named arguments are part of the language.nnThe second feature is the ability to defined default values for macro arguments:nn```jinjan{% macro input(name, value = , type = text, size = 20) %}n<input type={{ type }} name={{ name }} value={{ value|e }} size={{ size }} />n{% endmacro %}nn```nnMore information in the updated documentation.nnThese features have been implemented with BC in mind (which means that the code is not optimal, but it will be completely refactored for Twig 2.0 where we will get rid of all those ridiculous `Twig_Filter_*` and `Twig_Function_*` classes).nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-11-15T10:34:16ZnnI forgot to mention that there is no overhead if you are not using these new features, and that the overhead is only at compilation time (the compiled templates are the same as before).nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby marekkalnik at 2012-11-15T10:36:49ZnnThat are some great features, thanks ! :+1:nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby lolautruche at 2012-11-15T10:46:42ZnnNice ! :+1:n@fabpot So I guess the old behavior is kept, isn't it ?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fspillner at 2012-11-15T10:50:31ZnnAwesome!nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-11-15T11:28:20Znn@lolautruche yes, the old way still works of course.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Seldaek at 2012-11-15T11:42:40ZnnAwesome! This has been much needed a few times in the past. We can almost drop php altogether and just write twig :Pnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby marfillaster at 2012-11-15T12:07:43Znn@Seldaek maybe a twig to php processornn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Seldaek at 2012-11-15T12:14:34Znn@marfillaster that's already what twig is :)nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Tobion at 2012-11-15T12:38:28Znn@fabpot nice stuffnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby simensen at 2012-11-15T16:01:03ZnnThis looks great!nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby sstok at 2012-11-15T19:18:53ZnnThis was basically the only thing missing I was missing in Twign:100: :+1:nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby jorgelbg at 2012-11-15T20:05:15ZnnI love this new feauture, it's great to have this on Twig! Brings a lot of clarity to my future templates ;-)n

merged branch fabpot/tokenparserbroker (PR #903)This PR was merged into the master branch.nnCommitsn-------nn8563e04 deprecated the token parser broker sub-systemnnDiscussionn----------nndeprecated the token parser broker sub-systemnnThis is the first of a series of PRs where I want to deprecate some features that made sense at some point but do not anymore or features that are barely used. Deprecated features will still work in all versions of Twig 1.x but they will be removed in Twig 2.0.nnThis first one should not be controversial. The token parser broker was added at a time where functions in Twig were not available. Nowadays, creating a new tag is so rare that I cannot see any usage for the broker system.nnAs far as I know, nobody uses the broker system anyway (this feature is not even documented), except [Zwig](https://github.com/arnaud-lb/Zwig). And Zwig should probably create functions instead of tags for ZF helpers anyways.nnping @arnaud-lbnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby arnaud-lb at 2012-11-16T17:27:02ZnnIIRC the main reason for using this in Zwig was that ZF makes it hard to list helpers, and easy to get an helper by name. So the broken allows to use ZF helpers without listing them. The reason for using tags instead of functions is that many helpers in ZF are not used for their return value and/or printing. (Zwig also exposes helpers as functions, through registerUndefinedFunctionCallback, for those used for their return value or printing.)nnNo objection for removing in 2.x though.n

merged branch fabpot/callables-everywhere (PR #905)This PR was merged into the master branch.nnCommitsn-------nn1918ede added the ability to use any PHP callable to define filters, functions, and testsnnDiscussionn----------nnadded the ability to use any PHP callable to define filters, functions, and testsnnEverything is in the title.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Tobion at 2012-11-18T13:25:51ZnnAre filters etc. slower when defined as closures (instead of function definitions)?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-11-18T13:30:47Znn@Tobion No, it does not matter how they are defined. merged branch fabpot/render-function (PR #926)This PR was merged into the master branch.nnCommitsn-------nnf4f88a5 added an include functionnnDiscussionn----------nnadded an include functionnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-12-09T14:12:25ZnnI see an issue with this naming: it will confuse Symfony users because of the ``render`` tag doing something different than the ``render`` function. And it will force to break BC for Silex users where the subrequest logic is using a ``render`` function right nownn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-12-10T12:49:57Znn@stof: I know about the possible confusion. For Silex, as it is not stable yet, we don't need to keep BC. And I don't have any other better name. What I want to introduce next is a `render_request` function in both Silex and Symfony (which will do the same as the current render tag in Symfony and the render function in Silex).nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Taluu at 2012-12-10T14:13:31ZnnHi,nnI may be absent-minded, but I don't really understand the difference between `render` function and the `include` tag... ?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-12-10T14:16:09Znn@Taluu Using a function allows you to do whatever you want with the output (which is not possible with a tag), like a simple:nn```jinjan{{ set content = render('some_template') }}n```nnAlso, semantically, using a tag to output some content is less correct.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby vicb at 2012-12-10T14:18:17Znncould it be named `include` ?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby tcz at 2012-12-10T14:18:40ZnnI agree that it's confusing for Symfony users. It is the same as raw filter and raw tag. I would prefer execute as name or something like thatnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Taluu at 2012-12-10T14:19:29Znn@fabpot so, does it means that it could replace the include tag ? Then, we could could name it `include` as @vicb suggested... ?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby titomiguelcosta at 2012-12-10T14:21:51ZnnI agree with @stof, naming it render will be confusing, parse or execute or compile are other names that come to my mind for this purpose.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby silentworks at 2012-12-10T14:24:36ZnnHow about calling it `partial`? even though you are rendering a full template, it is being included in another so this could be seeing as a partial of that template.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-12-10T14:26:05Znn@titomiguelcosta parse is totally wrong. The function is not parsing the string you give it. you don't pass the content of the template but its name. and ``compile`` is also wrong. It is not compiling a template but rendering it.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby jmather at 2012-12-10T14:30:53ZnnI think `render` is probably the most appropriate name, but also may cause confusion, however I don't have another suggestion that is nearly as clear as to context and meaning.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby emgiezet at 2012-12-10T14:31:26ZnnCan you pass the array of params as an argument to the `render` function?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby titomiguelcosta at 2012-12-10T14:31:59Znn@stof true that we pass the filename as argument, but we end up parsing the file.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-12-10T14:32:48Znn@emgiezet you mean passing some variables available in the included template ? Sure you can. See the doc. the argument is named ``variables``nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-12-10T14:34:36Znn@titomiguelcosta But the goal of the function is not to parse the file (btw, it may not parse it if the template was already compiled in the cache). The goal is to render the template.nnBtw, I agree with @jmather. As far as Twig is concerned, ``render`` is the best name. The only issue comes from the fact that Symfony already use a ``{% render %}`` tag with a different meaningnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby emgiezet at 2012-12-10T14:39:02Znn@stof thx a lot didn't noticed the doc link. Maybe `render_partial` will be good in this case?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby tcz at 2012-12-10T14:44:13ZnnIn an ideal world the Symfony2 `render` tag would be renamed to `subrequest` or something like that and the new function in Twig would get the `render` name. The question is how many people use Twig because of Symfony2 and how many of them use it in itself (in my company we use standalone Twig for example).nnI think it's important to avoid `raw`-style confusions for the former group.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-12-10T15:16:28Znn@tcz The issue with renaming the tag in Symfony is that it would be a BC break. So we cannot simply drop the tag (we can provide a new name and deprecate the current one, but we would still keep it).nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Taluu at 2012-12-10T15:18:56ZnnI think `partial` would be a good idea... But still, does it mean that the `include` tag would be deprecated in favor of `render` (or whatever the name will be) function ?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby tcz at 2012-12-10T15:19:49Znn@stof Yes :( hence my remark in an ideal worldnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-12-10T15:27:52Znn@Taluu It depends if @fabpot wants to keep the compatibility with Jinja where possible (as it is where the ``include`` tag comes from)nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby WouterJ at 2012-12-10T15:48:26ZnnI like the function, but I don't like the name. I like the name `partial`.nnI am a front-end developer from origin and all files you include in the base CSS stylesheet are called 'partials' in SASS or other preprosessors. Twig is used to make live easier for front-end developers and I think a function called `partial` is more familiair for them than `render`.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby silentworks at 2012-12-10T16:17:24Znn@stof I guess based on @fabpot wanting to keep Twig compatibility with Jinja, calling the tag `partial` rather than `render` shouldn't be a problem since Jinja doesn't have any of these.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Taluu at 2012-12-10T16:19:25Znn@silentworks @stof was talking about my question, about why keep the `include` tag if the `render` (or whatever the name will be) is indeed inserted into Twig. :)nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-12-10T16:19:38Znn@silentworks I was not talking about the name of the function, but about the removal of the ``include`` tagnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby silentworks at 2012-12-10T16:22:37ZnnThanks for clarity from both.nnOn the basis of keeping to conformity to Jinja, should this function not be a part of twig extensions rather than in the core?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby mvrhov at 2012-12-10T17:20:03ZnnWell search and replace for symfony users when upgrading shouldn't be that hard so I'd say that we rename the symfony block into subrequest or sth similar.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Taluu at 2012-12-10T17:26:22ZnnIf we were to follow your recommandations, we could say the same for all and every changes inducing a BC break huh...nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby markstory at 2012-12-10T17:49:36ZnnWhat about naming the function `include`?  It would share a name with the tag, but it also does the same type of thing as the tag.  The function has the advantage of having its return captured.  I think  `{{ include(template) }}` semantically does what it looks like it does when operating on the template object as well.nnOther names that I think could fit well are `partial` and `display`. Render works well, but I understand people not wanting to overlap with existing symfony features that do very different things.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Baachi at 2012-12-10T18:13:25ZnnI think partial is a better name for this function and it would keep BC.n

Tests should pass now.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-12-31T14:55:29ZnnI think you are now forbidding to replace an existing global without calling ``getGlobals`` first when the runtime is initializednn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby dantleech at 2012-12-31T15:12:20ZnnI think that this is the correct logic.nnThrow the Exception Unable to add global %s as the runtime or  the extensions have already been initialized IF the global has not already been registered.nnSo, if ``$globals === null`` then this is indeed the case. merged branch fabpot/verbatim (PR #947)This PR was merged into the master branch.nnCommitsn-------nncd4ab0f renamed the raw tag to verbatim to avoid confusion with the raw filternnDiscussionn----------nnrenamed the raw tag to verbatim to avoid confusion with the raw filternnIn Twig, we have a `raw` tag and a raw filter. Unfortunately, they are totally unrelated and that is confusing.nnI propose to rename the `raw` tag to `verbatim`. Of course, for BC reasons, the old `raw` tag will be kept around for the foreseeable future as an alias to `verbatim`.nnFor the record, `raw` is used by Jinja (http://jinja.pocoo.org/docs/templates/#escaping), whereas `verbatim` was introduced in Django in 1.5 (https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/releases/1.5/#verbatim-template-tag).n

merged branch deadbeef84/getglobals-before-addglobal-bug (PR #990)This PR was merged into the master branch.nnCommitsn-------nn667b274 Added unit test for bug when calling getGlobals() before addGlobal() on Twig_Environment.nnDiscussionn----------nnBug when calling getGlobals() before addGlobal() on Twig_Environment.nnThere seems to be an issue when calling getGlobals() before addGlobal(), the globals wont get updated. It doesn't seem to matter if the global existed before the call to getGlobals(). An update of the globals can be forced by calling an additional getGlobals() after the addGlobal() call.nnI believe the problem has something to do with runtimeInitialized/extensionInitialized being set to true during rendering, but globals don't get updated during that phase.nnNot sure how to fix it so I'm just sending you a unit test showcasing the bug.n

merged branch andrewjbaker/force-timezone (PR #964)This PR was merged into the master branch.nnCommitsn-------nn999b1c4 Force timezone setting in date filternnDiscussionn----------nnForce timezone setting in date filternnIn instances where the $time parameter to the DateTime ctor includes a timezone, the $timezone argument is ignored. This functionality extends to the date filter.nnhttp://uk3.php.net/manual/en/datetime.construct.phpnnThe $timezone parameter and the current timezone are ignored when the $time parameter either is a UNIX timestamp (e.g. @946684800) or specifies a timezone (e.g. 2010-01-28T15:00:00+02:00).nnAccepting this pull request is dependent on whether the desired functionality of the date filter should honour the PHP way of doing things, or the more logical and natural functionality anticipated by a Twig template designer; always ensuring the timezone passed into the date filter is applied.n

merged branch fabpot/named-args (PR #1072)This PR was merged into the master branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnenforced usage of named arguments after positional onesnnWhen we introduced named arguments, the behavior for when both positional and named arguments were used in a call was not clearly defined.nnThis PR addresses this issue by following Python rules:nn * No positional argument after named onesn * No possibility to define an argument with both a positional argument and a named onennThis introduces a BC break if people were using positional arguments after named ones, but I would argue that this is never a good idea anyway.nnThis is an alternative to #995nnCommitsn-------nn135b618 enforced usage of named arguments after positional onesn

Corrected description of the // operatorThe operator was previously described to truncate the the value when it in fact floors the result of the division (which can be seen in https://github.com/fabpot/Twig/blob/master/lib/Twig/Node/Expression/Binary/FloorDiv.php#L20).rnBy the old description one would think that ``{{ -20 // 7 }}`` would yield -2 (as in ``(int)(-20/7)``) when it actually returns -3 (as in ``floor(-20/7)``). Floor is not truncate (cast to int).

minor #1333 Added disambiguation on using raw in expressions (OwlyCode)This PR was merged into the 1.16-dev branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnAdded disambiguation on using raw in expressionsnnI recently got in trouble using the ``raw`` filter in a ternary, leading to a value being escaped and me not expecting it. The code was :nn```n{{ foo|striptags|length > 250 ? foo|striptags|slice(0, 250) ~ '...' : foo|raw }}n```nnWhen foo's length was under 250 characters, the result of this expression was escaped. Here is the updated documentation to explain why.nnCommitsn-------nncec2b57 Added disambiguation on using raw in expressionsn

Fix for mb function overload mb_substr acting different

bug #1453 Fix for mb function overload mb_substr acting different (1emming)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.16-dev branch (closes #1453).nnDiscussionn----------nnFix for mb function overload mb_substr acting differentnnWhen bug hunting https://github.com/fabpot/Twig/issues/1428 I ran into an issue.nI started out by changing my `php.ini` for the `cli` enviroment, I've added:n`mbstring.func_overload = 2`nLater I tested with adding and removing:n`mbstring.internal_encoding = 'UTF-8'`nnIt turns out `mb_substr` returns `false` and not `''` when doing something like this:nn```phpn$item = '';n$start = -1;n$length = 1;n$charset = 'UTF-8';n$a = mb_substr($item, $start, $length, $charset);nvar_dump($a);ndie;n```nnI'm not sure this will fix 1428 since I don't have enough information for this, but this PR should at least fix one issue.nnCommitsn-------nn214fe52 Fix for mb function overload mb_substr acting differentn

minor #1457 Fixed the `matches` operator code example (brandonkelly)This PR was merged into the 1.16-dev branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnFixed the `matches` operator code examplennA customer just pointed out that your `matches` operator code example wasn't working for them, and it ended up being because its backslashes themselves needed to be escaped by additional backslashes. (I've verified this.)nnWhile I was editing it, I also switched to forwardslash delimiters on the regex, since those are much more commonly used than curly brackets. (I hadn't even been aware that curly brackets are allowed.) To back that assertion up, [PHP's official preg_quote() docs](http://php.net/manual/en/function.preg-quote.php) state:nn> The `/` is the most commonly used delimiter.nnCommitsn-------nn33dcbc8 Fixed the `matches` operator code examplen

minor #1520 date() documentation correction (brandonkelly)This PR was merged into the 1.16-dev branch.nnDiscussionn----------nndate() documentation correctionnnThe date() docs were incorrectly stating that the argument should be in a format supported by PHPu00e2u0080u0099s [date()](http://php.net/manual/en/function.date.php) function. Thatu00e2u0080u0099s true of the |date filter which is used to _format_ dates, but not the date() function, which is used to _create_ new dates.nnI double-checked the code and whatever you pass into date() ultimately will get passed to a [DateTime constructor](http://php.net/manual/en/datetime.construct.php), which accepts an actual date string, formatted in one of PHPu00e2u0080u0099s [date and time format](http://php.net/manual/en/datetime.formats.php), which is a different beast than the actual format definition string you might pass into PHPu00e2u0080u0099s date() function.nnCommitsn-------nn2f5a927 date() documentation correctionn

feature #1503 Use LimitIterator on Iterable objects within the slice filter (Anthony Sterling)This PR was merged into the 1.16-dev branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnUse LimitIterator on Iterable objects within the slice filternnPreviously the `slice` filter would create an array of items if the subject to be sliced implemented Traversable, this PR instead passes the subject to LimitIterator first - but only if `$start` and `$length` are positive values as LimitIterator does not support the n'th from end behaviour.nnOur use case is that we have an API client, which we pass to slice, that implements Traversable but lazy loads the items to be returned via an API when `Iterator::current()` is called. Here a quick example:-nn```n{% for item in client.items | slice(0,5) %}n{{ item.name }}n{% endfor %}nnnn{% for item in client.items | slice(5,10) %}n{{ item.name }}n{% endfor %}n```nnCurrent behaviour would mean that the client would issue 15 requests to the API, 5 for the first block, and 10 for the second (but only return items 5 to 10). This PR means only 10 requests are made, 5 in each block.nnI'd imagine this would lower memory usage too.nnCommitsn-------nnfdddb1c Use LimitIterator on Iterable objects within the splice filtern

bug #1449 Fixed the date filter's timezone not being set correctly with strings (gbouchez)This PR was merged into the 1.16-dev branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnFixed the date filter's timezone not being set correctly with stringsnnWhen the date filter is used on a string and the timezone argument is specified, the timezone is ignored because of this :nn$date = new DateTime($date, $defaultTimezone);nif (false !== $timezone) {n$date->setTimezone($defaultTimezone);n}nnSince the date is initialized with `$defaultTimezone` as its timezone, using `$date->setTimezone($defaultTimezone);` has no effect, and the date is displayed without changes since it is considered to already be from this timezone.nnMight fix issue #1340nnCommitsn-------nn44aaa5b Fixed the date filter's timezone not being set correctly with stringsn

feature #1597 added a profiler (fabpot)This PR was merged into the 1.17-dev branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnadded a profilernnThis profiler allows to better understand what's going on when rendering templates. It should be used when debug is true only as it adds some overhead.nnHere is a sample output in the text format:nn```nmain 567.04ms/100%nu00e2u0094u0094 index 463.28ms/82%n  u00e2u0094u0094 base 463.24ms/82%nu00e2u0094u0094 base::block(header)nu00e2u0094u0094 index::block(content) 306.29ms/54%nu00e2u0094u0082 u00e2u0094u0094 included 50.18ms/9%nu00e2u0094u0082 u00e2u0094u0094 included 45.42ms/8%nu00e2u0094u0082 u00e2u0094u0094 included 35.42ms/6%nu00e2u0094u0082 u00e2u0094u0094 base::block(content) 104.97ms/19%nu00e2u0094u0082 u00e2u0094u0082 u00e2u0094u0094 included 34.90ms/6%nu00e2u0094u0082 u00e2u0094u0094 included 35.84ms/6%nu00e2u0094u0094 base::block(footer) 156.84ms/28%n  u00e2u0094u0094 included 38.96ms/7%n  u00e2u0094u0094 base::macro(foo)n```nnYou can also dump a profile in a Blackfire compatible format to [visualise the data as a graph](http://goo.gl/RwNGFH).nnA profile is also a great way to be able to list all templates/blocks/macros that were used when rendering a template.nnA PR on Symfony (symfony/symfony#13428) integrates this profiler in the Symfony web profiler to replace the current TimedTwigEngine and to add a new Twig panel.nn![symfony-web-profiler](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/47313/5755461/019cd6a4-9ca5-11e4-8762-68e2a709c336.png)nnCommitsn-------nn4408caa added a profilern

Reduce the name of the cache directories to 1 character

minor #1684 Reduce the name of the cache directories to 1 character (Nicofuma)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnReduce the name of the cache directories to 1 characternnCurrently Twig spread the cached template over a directory tree and it's a good practice because it makes the filesystem happier (some filesystems limit the number of file per directory and some filesystems do not index the content of the directories => to access a file in a directory you may have to go through all the files in the directory to find it).nnBut this technique as also a few drawbacks because it will consume more inodes and in PHP because of the realpath cache which could be saturated by the path of too many directories.nn`----`nnThe current implementation use 2 levels of directory with a 2 chars name, which end-up to `36^4 == 1,679,616` combinations and when you have a lot of templates it can be a real issue.nnPer example, with 8,000 templates you will have:n- 8,000 different keys because `8,000 <<< 1,679,616` (a key is the combination of the two directories name, so 4 characters)n- 1,296 directories directly under `twig/`n- **1 file** per directoryn- a total of `8,000 + 8,000 + 1,296 =` **17,296 keys** in the realpath cache.nnMy proposal with this PR is to reduce the name of the directories to only one character which for 8,000 templates end up to:n- 1,296 different keys (a key is the combination of the two directories name, so 2 characters)n- 36 directories directly under `twig/`n- ~**8 files** per directoryn- a total of `8,000 + 1,296 + 36 =` **9,332 keys** in the realpath cache.nnNote: If you don't have a lot of templates (> 1,000) it will not change anything for you.nnCommitsn-------nn2972309 Reduce the name of the cache directories to 1 charactern

minor #1796 OPcache support fix (iKwinto)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.x branch (closes #1796).nnDiscussionn----------nnOPcache support fixnnAccording this recipe http://twig.sensiolabs.org/doc/recipes.html#refreshing-modified-templates-when-opcache-or-apc-is-enabled when using OPcache:nn```nclass Twig_Environment_APC extends Twig_Environmentn{nprotected function writeCacheFile($file, $content)n{nparent::writeCacheFile($file, $content);nn// Compile cached file into bytecode cachenif (extension_loaded('Zend OPcache') && ini_get('opcache.enable')) {nopcache_compile_file($file);n} elseif (extension_loaded('apc') && ini_get('apc.enabled')) {napc_compile_file($file);n}n}n}n```nnit takes an error:nn```nCannot redeclare class __TwigTemplate_12e7606b10ee267fa4174f660f86451aed936cc5680300a6442092f337c910cfn```nnThis is due to fact that the function ```opcache_compile_file($file)``` executes the file. But it should not do so in accordance with the documentation: http://php.net/manual/en/function.opcache-compile-file.phpnnThere is a bug report: https://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=66066 (since 2013 :-1:).nnThis patch prevents reexecution of the compiled template.nnCommitsn-------nn2c4af24 OPcache support fixn

feature #1812 Extracted the filesystem cache to its own class (andrewtch, fabpot)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnExtracted the filesystem cache to its own classnnTwig caches the compiled PHP classes on the filesystem. This is **always** the best strategy as it allows Twig to automatically benefit from PHP opcache/APC. But overriding how the classes are stored on the filesystem is difficult with the current way, so this PR proposes to extract this logic to its own class (that should allow Drupal to stop copy/pasting some Twig code and accessing private code - see #1811).nnThis PR also unifies the no-cache feature by extracting it to its own class as well.nnBC is kept and the `false` and `$dir` caching strategies are still supported.nnThe `Twig_Cache_Interface` can be used to create other cache classes, but that's not documented and should only be used with extreme care (performance-wise). It means that Twig itself will **never** ship with other implementations like Memcache, Redis, whatever storage is hype nowadays. This should fix #1421 (this PR builds on top of it), #1573, #1415, #741, #728.nnCommitsn-------nncacfb06 added a cache interface for templatesn04cc7e4 Implemented filesystem cache, one and only (see #1415)n

Non-existing files are not cached by statcacheReverts #1583rnrnBased on the docs this cannot happen because the stat cache is only active for existing files.rnrn> You should also note that PHP doesn't cache information about non-existent files. So, if you call file_exists() on a file that doesn't exist, it will return FALSE until you create the file. If you create the file, it will return TRUE even if you then delete the file. However unlink() clears the cache automatically.rnrnhttp://php.net/manual/en/function.clearstatcache.phprnrnAlso the arugments you pass to clearstatcache(false, $filename) make no sense according the documentation and are not effective.rnrn> filenamernClear the realpath and the stat cache for a specific filename only; only used if clear_realpath_cache is TRUE.rnrnAlso doctrine cachee does't use this approach either: https://github.com/doctrine/cache/blob/master/lib/Doctrine/Common/Cache/FileCache.php#L185 And nobody reported problems with this as far as I can see.

Fix custom escaper null values

bug #1855 Fix custom escaper null values (moufmouf)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.x branch (closes #1855).nnDiscussionn----------nnFix custom escaper null valuesnnFirst, a bit of context:nnAbout 10 years ago, when I was doing some Java, I used to use a SQL mapper called iBatis (now moved to myBatis here: http://mybatis.github.io/mybatis-3/dynamic-sql.html)nThe whole concept is to put SQL requests in XML files and use XML as a templating engine. Here is a code sample:nn```xmln  SELECT * FROM BLOGn  WHERE state = u00e2u0080u0098ACTIVEu00e2u0080u0099n  <if test=title != null>nAND title like #{title}n  </if>n```nnFast forward today. I just realized Twig could be a great tool to do exactly the same. Just imagine:nn```SQLn  SELECT * FROM BLOGn  WHERE state = u00e2u0080u0098ACTIVEu00e2u0080u0099n  {% if title %}nAND title like {{ title }}n  {% endif %}n```nnAll I need to do is write a custom escaper. Like this one:nn```phpn$twig->getExtension('core')->setEscaper('sql', function(Twig_Environment $env, $string, $charset) use ($connection) {n// $connection is a DBAL connectionnreturn $connection->quote($string);n});n```nnNow, here is my problem:nnFor an SQL escaper to work, I would need *null* to translate into the 'NULL' string.nnBut in Twig, escapers are not triggered for null or numeric values. This is due to these lines of code: https://github.com/twigphp/Twig/blob/1.x/lib/Twig/Extension/Core.php#L1021-L1027nn```phpnif (!is_string($string)) {nif (is_object($string) && method_exists($string, '__toString')) {n$string = (string) $string;n} else {nreturn $string;n}n}n```nnEverything that is not a string (i.e. a numeric value, null, an array...) is directly returned and completely bypasses the escaper.nnI understand that this behaviour is ok in most cases (html, js, css, url, etc...), and that it allows some degree of optimisation, but it prevents from working on more specific escapers like a SQL escaper. It is also an undocumented behaviour of custom escapers.nnThis pull request tries to fix this without impacting performance.nnIn most Twig installations, no custom escapers are used. In this cases, returning early is a good idea since all default escapers share the same behaviour.nIf there is a custom escaper configured however, I'm going the long route to be sure that the custom escaper is fed with all values (and not only non empty strings)nnCommitsn-------nn6f84981 Fix custom escaper null valuesn

feature #1886 deprecated Twig_ExtensionInterface::initRuntime() (fabpot)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nndeprecated Twig_ExtensionInterface::initRuntime()nnI'm working on splitting Twig extensions into 2 different phases: compilation and runtime. The goal is to avoid having to load the runtime environment of an extension when compiling templates. That also opens the way to be able to lazy-load Twig extensions.nnWhile working on the split, I realized that the `initRuntime()` method on `Twig_ExtensionInterface` is not needed anymore. It was added at a time `needs_environment` did not exist and was a way to keep the environment around for custom filters/tests/functions. But nowadays, that's not needed anymore. I did a quick search on Github, and most of the implementation I found just store the environment in a local property, which is not needed anymore. So, I propose to deprecate it in 1.x and remove it in 2.0.nnCommitsn-------nn9774f4f deprecated Twig_ExtensionInterface::initRuntime()n

Fix Parser context push on stack

bug #1930 Fix Parser context push on stack (molaux)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.x branch (closes #1930).nnDiscussionn----------nnFix Parser context push on stacknnHello,nnWith php7RC8, in Twig_Parser, parse method starts by saving current context inncopying self properties on stack. It sounds like get_object_vars returns nownreferences instead of copies of properties (at least for arrays). Consequently,nwhen reinitializing Parser for subparse line 92 to 99, the preserved context onnstack was also erased.nnAs a result, when calling {{ parent() }} after a {%embed%}{%endembed%}, the restored blockStack being empty, Twig throws a Twig_Error_Syntax('Calling parent outside a block is forbidden.'), despite the fact it is really in a block that extends another.nWhen calling {{ parent() }} before  the embed tag, all works properly. (It seems that the empty context, resulting of subparses, is not a problem as far as you don't need to access it)nnCommitsn-------nn07ebdfe Fix Parser context push on stackn

feature #1964 undeprecated _self (fabpot)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnundeprecated _selfnnUn-deprecated `_self`. As mentioned in #1932, `_self` is sometimes used to get the current template name, which is a legitimate usage and almost always the user intent. Moreover, when `_self` is used in a template, it is mostly passed to Twig functions that are able to deal with Twig templates or Twig template names indifferently.nnfixes #1932nnCommitsn-------nnb490e65 undeprecated _selfn

feature #1889 marked some Twig_Environment methods as being internal (fabpot)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnmarked some Twig_Environment methods as being internalnnThis PR marks some `Twig_Environment` methods as being internals:nn * `getFunctions()`, `getFilters()`, `getTests()`, `getFunction()`, `getFilter()`, `getTest()`, `getTokenParsers()`, `getTags()`, `getNodeVisitors()`, `getUnaryOperators()`, `getBinaryOperators()` because I don't see how they can be used in any useful way and anyway, `getFunctions()` and `getFilters()` do not return all possible functions or filters. Moreover, I think that all this logic could be refactored and moved into its own class for 2.0 (could be done by deprecating those existing methods in 1.x if we agree to merge this PR).nn * `getGlobals()` because it should only be called in a runtime context, not in a compilation one (so limiting its usage to internal use only allows for better control of usage).nn * `initGlobals()`, `initExtensions()`, `initExtension()` because they are private in Twig 2.0.nnCommitsn-------nn212730a marked some Twig_Environment methods as being internaln

fix a case where the autoescaping does not work as expectedThe Twig_NodeVisitor_Escaper collects a list of blocks for all templates that it visits. If you define the same block (i.e. with the same name) in txt and html templates this results sometimes in the html block not being escapes.nnThis is illustrated in the added test.nnTo fix it, I propose to reset the list of the blocks for each module.nnAlternatively we need to make clear that blocks should not share names between text and html templates.n
Reset blocks also in doLeaveNode

Improved the error message when a child template defines contents outside parent blocks

minor #2139 Improved the error message when a child template defines contents outside parent blocks (javiereguiluz)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.x branch (closes #2139).nnDiscussionn----------nnImproved the error message when a child template defines contents outside parent blocksnn### ContextnnWhen using template inheritance, you cannot put template contents outside Twig blocks (except some special tags (form_theme), macros, etc.) Sadly, making this mistake is very common when learning Twig.nn### ProblemnnThe error message associated to this issue is cryptic and impossible to understand for newcomers:nn```nA template that extends another one cannot have a body.n```nnI recently delivered a Symfony training and nobody was able to understand what the error was. They didn't have the slightest clue. I explained it to them ... and a few days latter they had the same problem and again they couldn't remember what this error was related to.nn### SolutionnnMost of the Twig/Symfony errors are very helpful. Let's improve this one to make it useful too.nnTwo years ago I tried to fix this error message (see #1396). Let's see if this new PR is accepted.nnCommitsn-------nn23f53d5 Improved the error message when a child template defines contents outside parent blocksn

Load templates from cache, even if they have just been compiled

bug #2216 Load templates from cache, even if they have just been compiled (mpdude)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.x branch (closes #2216).nnDiscussionn----------nnLoad templates from cache, even if they have just been compilednnPreviously, when the cache was empty, the compiled template would be written to it, but `eval()`d from `$content`. In that case, it is not possible to step through (read: debug) the compiled template because at least xDebug does not have a clue where the code comes from.nnWith this change, PHP/xDebug can tell even on the first run (with an empty cache) where the code was loaded from.nnCommitsn-------nnff0abbb Load templates from cache, even if they have just been compiledn
