feature #2245 added support for a custom template on the block() function (fabpot)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnadded support for a custom template on the block() functionnn`block()` allows one to render a block of the current template.nnThis PR adds the possibility to use `block()` to render a block of another template:nn```twign{{ block('footer', template_name) }}n```nnAs it uses the same logic as for the regular `block()`, you can also use it in a test:nn```twign{% if block('footer', template_name) is defined %}n...n{% endif %}n```nnThis removes the needs to use the internal `Twig_Template::renderBlock()` method in the Symfony Web Profiler for instance. And combined with #2236, it allows us to really mark the whole `Twig_Template` class as being internal.nnI'm aware that #1302 asked for being able to pass a context to `block()` (implemented in #1433), but I prefer not to in favor of adding the `with` tag (see #719 and #1054).nnWhen the `with` will be implemented, the code in the Symfony Web Profiler will become something along the lines of:nn```twign{% with {n'collector': profile.getcollector(name),n'profiler_url': profiler_url,n'token': profile.token,n'name': namen  } %}n{{ block('toolbar', template) }}n{% endwith %}n```nnCommitsn-------nn5ed59be added support for a custom template on the block() functionn

feature #2249 Remove optimization as it's not compatible with Symfony cache system (fabpot)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnRemove optimization as it's not compatible with Symfony cache systemnnfixes #2243nn@nicolas-grekas Instead of fixing Symfony cache system (which will only happen in a new patch release), I propose to revert these changes. It means no optimization for Twig 1.x, but the optimization is the default in Twig 2.0. So, I don't think this is a big deal.nnCommitsn-------nnd64d320 removed optimization as it's not compatible with Symfony cache systemn

feature #2236 Expose a way to access template data and methods in a portable way (fabpot)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnExpose a way to access template data and methods in a portable waynn`Twig_Template` is an internal class, and most of its methods are marked as being `@internal` as they are not safe to use by end users.nnBut some of its features are interesting like `renderBlock()` which is very useful when rendering emails for instance (see #1873).nnThis PR tries to address both issues by marking the whole `Twig_Template` class as being internal  and by exposing a new way to safely interact with a template besides the obvious `render()`/`display()` methods via `$twig->load(...)`.nnIf also add some convenient methods like `hasBlock()` or `getBlocks()` (see ~#1831~ and #1882):nn```phpn$template = $twig->load('index');nnecho $template->render($context);n$template->display($context);nnif ($template->hasBlock('name') {n   $template->displayBlock('name', $context);n}nnforeach ($template->getBlocks() as $block) {necho $template->render($block, $context);n}n```nnCommitsn-------nnd7062f3 exposed a way to access template data and methods in a portable wayn

minor #2253 Use ** operator over function pow() (SpacePossum)This PR was submitted for the master branch but it was merged into the 2.x branch instead (closes #2253).nnDiscussionn----------nnUse ** operator over function pow()nnWith Twig PHP dep. raised to 5.6 the arithmetic operator [`**`](http://php.net/manual/en/language.operators.arithmetic.php) can be used.nnBesides slightly faster it is also harder to override an operator than it is the `pow()` function.nnCommitsn-------nn97f8159 Use ** operator over function pow()n
added support for PHP 7 null coalescing operator

feature #2250 Add support for PHP 7 null coalescing operator (fabpot)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnAdd support for PHP 7 null coalescing operatornnThis is just one case where we can optimize the ternary operator. PHP 7 also supports more complex expressions that can return `null`. The rule here seems to be that you cannot have more than one level of undefinedness.nnSo, for instance, if `log` is defined, `log(foo) ?? NOPE` works, but `log($a[foo]) ?? NOPE` does not if `$a[foo]` is not defined. If we want to convert the code to always use `??` when possible, this should probably be implemented in the Optimizer node visitor, not here. But the question is: is it worth it in terms of performance? It cleans up the generated code quite a bit though.nncloses #1979nnCommitsn-------nncfc3931 added support for PHP 7 null coalescing operatorn

feature #2311 Add a simple Twig_RuntimeLoaderInterface implementation (chalasr)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnAdd a simple Twig_RuntimeLoaderInterface implementationnnNext to https://github.com/symfony/symfony/pull/21023nnThis is related to the BC break reported in symfony/symfony#21008 which has been introduced in symfony/symfony#20093 when decoupling extensions from definitions.nnWhat I propose here is to ease the upgrade to symfony 3.2+ by adding a simple `Twig_RuntimeLoaderInterface` implementation here, useful only when using the twig-bridge outside of the symfony fullstack framework (with the Form component for instance).nnUpgrading would be as simple as:nn```diffn$twig = new Twig_Environment(...);n$rendererEngine = new TwigRendererEngine(array('form_div_layout.html.twig'), $twig);n- $twig->addExtension(new FormExtension(new TwigRenderer($rendererEngine, $csrfTokenManager)));n+ $twig->addExtension(new FormExtension());n+ $twig->addRuntimeLoader(new Twig_RuntimeLoader(array(TwigRenderer::class => new TwigRenderer($rendererEngine, $csrfTokenManager)));n```nnInstead of having to write this runtime loader yourself.nPlease see symfony/symfony#21008 for details and a concrete example of how this could help.nnCommitsn-------nn91c8d59 Add a Twig_FactoryRuntimeLoadern

bug #2354 Turned fatal error into exception when a previously generated cache prevents loading its newly compiled version (nicolas-grekas)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnTurned fatal error into exception when a previously generated cache prevents loading its newly compiled versionnnNot sure if this is testable, yet this should save some hours to people that end up in the same trap we did on our project.nIt turned out we generated some twig template cache in two separate commands, in a situation where index tracking for embeds where lost.nnThis PR detects the situation and invites to clear the cache properly, because that's the only way to fix the issue.nnIt also fixes a mistake in the cache $key generation, that should not take $index into account.nDoing so were making offline cache warmup useless in some situations.nnCommitsn-------nn95c10991 Turned fatal error into exception when a previously generated cache prevents loading its newly compiled versionn

Use null rather than specific length for 'all characters to the end' with mb_substr

bug #2366 Use null rather than specific length for 'to the end' in mb_substr (arjenm)This PR was merged into the 2.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnUse null rather than specific length for 'to the end' in mb_substrnnWe use Twig with a ISO-8859-15 charset and noticed the 'capitalize'-method only yielded the first character of a string. I.e. abcd became A rather than Abcd.nnThis was due to a change in the way mb_substr is used. Appearantly, using 2147483647 as a length to indicate 'everything to the end' only works with UTF-8 (and possibly other multibyte charsets). It probably triggers some internal overflow in php for at least ASCII and ISO-8859-15.nnLuckily, an easy fix is available since PHP 5.4.8: just use 'null'nnSee these two tests for which version does what:n(old) https://3v4l.org/qdpIKn(new) https://3v4l.org/kivqKnnI also used null in the slice-method. While it did not suffer from this same issue, it did an unnecessary mb_strlen. And there might be similar overflow issues with negative values of $start, but I didn't actually test that.nnCommitsn-------nn3bea610e Use null rather than specific length for 'all characters to the end' with mb_substrn

bug #2427 Fixed JS escaping for unicode characters with higher code points (mikealmond)This PR was submitted for the 2.x branch but it was merged into the 1.x branch instead (closes #2427).nnDiscussionn----------nnFixed JS escaping for unicode characters with higher code pointsnnUnicode characters with higher code points were being escaped incorrectly. When these characters are escaped, they should maintain their surrogate halves. Previously, Twig was dropping the first surrogate half.nnhttps://mathiasbynens.be/notes/javascript-escapes#unicode-code-pointn> The tetragram for centre symbol (u00f0u009du008cu0086) has code point U+1D306, so you could write it as u{1D306}. For comparison, if you were to use simple Unicode escapes to represent this symbol, youu00e2u0080u0099d have to write out the surrogate halves separately: 'uD834uDF06'.nnCommitsn-------nn7f913495 Fixed JS escaping for unicode characters with higher code pointsn

Make length filter and empty test consider __toString [Twig 1.x]

feature #2420 Make length filter and empty test consider __toString [Twig 1.x] (mpdude)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.x branch (closes #2420).nnDiscussionn----------nnMake length filter and empty test consider __toString [Twig 1.x]nnUse case: When you have variables in your views that are actually objects but implement `__toString`, they feel like strings: For example, `{{ something }}` will make use of that to-string-conversion.nnWhat does *not* work isnn**a)** `{{ something | length }}`, because that will only have a meaningful return value for objects implementing `Countable`. This interface, however, may have a totally different semantic/purpose for the object in question.nn**b)** `{% if something is empty %}`, becausenn> empty checks if a variable is an empty string, an empty array, an empty hash, exactly false, or exactly null  `[http://twig.sensiolabs.org/doc/2.x/tests/empty.html]`nn... and obviously `something !== null` in this case.nnFor template designers, this may be surprising if they don't actually care about the object-or-string difference, they just use the variable.nnThis change tries to address this as it changes the behavior for  such objects that have a `__toString` method and are *not* `Countable`.nn*Yes*, it's a BC break in edge cases:nnFor a), objects that implement a `__toString` but not `Countable` would previously yield `1` for `{{ object |u00c2u00a0length }}`, and now would return the length of the string returned by `__toString`.nnFor b), testing (defined) variables that are objects implementing  `__toString` and that return `''`,  the test now is `false`.nnCommitsn-------nnf5193e92 Make length filter and empty test consider __toString [Twig 1.x]n

Autoescape test addition; collision fix in Array Loader.

minor #2434 Autoescape test addition; collision fix in Array Loader. (dave-newson)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.x branch (closes #2434).nnDiscussionn----------nnAutoescape test addition; collision fix in Array Loader.nnThis PR makes two changes. It was created while testing a third issue that was discovered to be fixed in the latest version.nn## Added JS to Autoescape: name testnnThis adds index.js.html to the autoescape:name test, proving the functionality of the JS escape system and the name guessing strategy.nn## Fixed collision in Array LoadernnWhile trying to run the above test, it was discovered that the Array Loader uses the content of the template file as the key for determining which compiled template to load.nAs the above test uses identical content for both HTML and JS templates this led to the compiled HTML template always being loaded.nnThis change prepends the content with the filename, which vaguely follows the same mechanism as the options (which are appended after `getCacheKey` is called).nn**This change might be a backwards-incompatible change** depending on your interpretation of how `Loader/Array` is intended to be used.nThe class itself states:n> This loader should only be used for unit testing.nnThe assumption is it's OK for this to occur.nnTest cases have been updated to take this key change into account, and an additional test has been added to confirm `Loader/Array` specifically has the capability to resolve two files with the same content to different keys.nnCommitsn-------nnda82b41a Autoescape test addition; collision fix in Array Loader.n

feature #2530 Throw exception on circular reference detection (yceruto)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnThrow exception on circular reference detectionnnOut-the-box this isn't common... but into Symfony framework this kind of issue can happen frequently when we're overriding a template from third-party bundle (see main issue https://github.com/symfony/symfony/issues/17557)nn```twign{# app/Resources/AcmeBlogBundle/views/Blog/index.html.twig #}n{% extends '@AcmeBlog/Blog/index.html.twig' %}nn{% block title 'New Title' %}n```nnThis exception avoids inifite loop or maximum execution time for this case, by detecting a recursive loading when a template extends from itself, thinking to override the parent template which has the same namespace + template name.nnCommitsn-------nn074e1fbe Throw exception on circular reference detectionn

Add JSON escape strategy

bug #2581 Add JSON escape strategy (c960657)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.x branch (closes #2581).nnDiscussionn----------nnAdd JSON escape strategynnThe `js` escape strategy used `u00NN`-style escape sequences. This is not allowed in JSON, only `uNNNN` is allowed.nnThis PR adds a new escape strategy, `json` that is similar to `js` except that it does not use `u00NN` but uses `uNNNN` instead.nnI know that I can use `json_decode()`, but it came as a surprise to me that `escape('js')` did not work. You probably shouldn't be generating JSON structures in your templates, but sometimes it comes in handy. My use-case was generating a piece of [JSON-LD](https://json-ld.org).nnA different approach that would perhaps be less confusing to users would be to change `js` to not use `u00NN`. This output is still valid JavaScript, it just uses two more bytes per occurrence. Let me know what you think.nnCommitsn-------nn5c7b080b Add JSON escape strategyn

minor #2668 Small optimization for Twig_NodeTraverser::traverseForVisitor (covex-nn)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnSmall optimization for Twig_NodeTraverser::traverseForVisitornnDuring traversing a node tree `Twig_NodeTraverser::traverseForVisitor` (`Twig_NodeVisitorInterface::leaveNode`) often returns a same child node (a same object). So, there is no need to set it back to its parent.nnThis PR adds a check if a child node was changed. With this check a lot of calls to `Twig_Node::setNode` will be skipped.nnCloses #2665nnCommitsn-------nn555d01f3 Small optimization for Twig_NodeTraverser::traverseForVisitorn

minor #2670 Fix partial template caching after update when auto_reload is on (ay-git)This PR was submitted for the 2.x branch but it was merged into the 1.x branch instead (closes #2670).nnDiscussionn----------nnFix partial template caching after update when auto_reload is onnn**Description of the bug:**nThis bug manifests itself on production servers.nAnd with a high load the probability of getting on this bug tends to 100%nThe bug results in the caching of a partial template and the failure of a part of the site working with this template. Can only be corrected by deleting the cache.nn**What's happening:**nIf in the process of uploading the template file, a render() is called, the partially uploaded file gets into the cache and after the template file is fully uploaded, the cache is not updated anymore.nn**How to demonstrate:**nTo demonstrate the bug, you can create 2 files:nFile simulating the download of a file to the server (twig_test_write.php):nn```n$classTwig = new Twig_Environment( new Twig_Loader_Filesystem(__DIR__./../../site_templates/), array(nt'cache' => __DIR__.'/../../site_templates_cache',nt'auto_reload'=>truen));nnfile_put_contents(__DIR__./../../site_templates/.test.twig,n
Template start write to filesystem);nnecho $classTwig->render(test.twig, array());nnfile_put_contents(__DIR__./../../site_templates/.test.twig, - Template end write to filesystem,FILE_APPEND);nn```nnFile for template rendering (twig_test_read.php):n```n$classTwig = new Twig_Environment( new Twig_Loader_Filesystem(__DIR__./../../site_templates/), array(nt'cache' => __DIR__.'/../../site_templates_cache',nt'auto_reload'=>truen));nnecho $classTwig->render(test.twig, array());n```nnResult executeing file twig_test_write.php:n```nTemplate start write to filesystemn```nnResult executeing file twig_test_read.php:n```nTemplate start write to filesystemn```nn**After this fix:**nResult executeing file twig_test_read.php:n```nTemplate start write to filesystem - Template end write to filesystemn```nnCommitsn-------nn50d990e2 Fix cache update after uploading the template file (when auto-update is enabled).n

feature #2687 Deprecate the possibility to define a block in a non-capturing block from a child template (fabpot)This PR was merged into the 2.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnDeprecate the possibility to define a block in a non-capturing block from a child templatennfixes #351, #541, #703, #988, #1639, #1685, #2393nnOne recurring issue (see the probably non-exhaustive list of issues references above) is a misunderstanding of how blocks work in a child template.nnFor instance, there is no way to define a `block` conditionally:nn```twign{% extends layout %}nn{% if ... %}n{% block content %}n...n{% endblock %}n{% endif %}n```nnAnd wrapping a `block` definition with a `spaceless` tag does not work:nn```twign{% extends layout %}nn{% spaceless %}n{% block content %}n...n{% endblock %}n{% endspaceless %}n```nnThe issue is that the above templates compile just fine, but not in a way people expect. Basically, the condition would be empty.nnInterestingly enough, wrapping a `block` definition might be useful/work as expected when used with capturing tags like `set`:nn```twign{% extends layout %}nn{% set content %}n{% block content %}n...n{% endblock %}n{% endset %}n```nnNot sure if that's useful, but here, the `block` tag will serve as the blog definition AND it will also be displayed in place. I would not recommend such usages.nnThis pull request deprecates the cases where the compiled template would never reflect the developer intent, but keeps the working scenarii as is.nnI've been trying to fix that issue for **years**. Very happy to have found a simple solution without breaking anything that worked fine.nnCommitsn-------nn9b938887 deprecated the possibility to define a block in a non-capturing block from a child templaten

Report the proper location for errors compiled in templatesThe {% use %} and {% with %} tags are adding some runtime checks triggeringnexceptions in the compiled template. This ensures that they get the propernlocation.nWhile the guessing was generally working fine for the {% with %} (and so thisnonly makes the code faster), the guessing was not working for {% use %} duento the exception happening in the class constructor rather than on displayn(and so the guessing was finding the template which was triggering the loadnof the faulty template).n

bug #2701 Ensure that syntax errors are triggered with the right line (stof)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnEnsure that syntax errors are triggered with the right linennWhen throwing the syntax error without any line and source in these places, the guessing logic enters into action. For the main template, it won't find anything. But for included templates (or any other template loaded during the rendering of another one, even as main one), the guessing will find a template (the caller one) and set the source and line based on it. The source will then be replaced by the proper template by `Twig_Environment::compileSource`, but the guessed line number will make no sense then.nnI searched for all places triggering a syntax error in Twig, to ensure that they always set the actual line number or set the source directly (so that the guessing logic knows that the template it found is the wrong one and so does not try to use it for guessing). There were only a few missing ones.nnCommitsn-------nn6fab6b0b Ensure that syntax errors are triggered with the right linen
Merge branch '1.x' into 2.x* 1.x:n  Ensure that syntax errors are triggered with the right linen  fix a typon

bug #2700 Report the proper location for errors compiled in templates (stof)This PR was merged into the 2.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnReport the proper location for errors compiled in templatesnnThe `{% use %}` and `{% with %}` tags are adding some runtime checks triggering exceptions in the compiled template. This ensures that they get the proper location.nWhile the guessing was generally working fine for the `{% with %}` (and so this only makes the code faster), the guessing was not working for `{% use %}` due to the exception happening in the class constructor rather than on display (and so the guessing was finding the template which was triggering the load of the faulty template).nnCommitsn-------nne4423576 Report the proper location for errors compiled in templatesn

bug #2702 Fix the error handling for the optimized extension-based function calls (stof)This PR was merged into the 2.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnFix the error handling for the optimized extension-based function callsnnTriggering a Twig_Error_Runtime at compile-time breaks the contract of the Twig environment, as such exception is for errors during the rendering.nThis moves back the exception to a runtime one (same behavior than before the optimization).nnAnother option would be to replace this with a `Twig_Error_Syntax` instead (reporting the error earlier), but that would change the exception being thrown for such case.nnCommitsn-------nn9928ae14 Fix the error handling for the optimized extension-based function callsn

feature #2696 [RFC] Added new deprecated tag (yceruto)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nn[RFC] Added new deprecated tagnn```twign{% deprecated 'The message...' %}n```nnThis new tag would allow us to define a deprecation warning anywhere within a template, useful for Frameworks, bundles, etc. where breaking the BC is frequently when templates are involved.nnIt will be easy to guarantee a smooth migration path when we want e.g. rename/remove a template or block, as well as displaying an accurate depreciation message.nn**Deprecating a whole template `{# base.twig #}`**n```twign{% deprecated 'The ' ~ _self ~ ' template is deprecated, use layout.twig instead' %}nn{% extends 'layout.twig' %}n```nIf we're extending from this template `{% extends 'base.twig' %}` then:n```nThe base.twig template is deprecated, use layout.twig instead (base.twig at line 1).n```n**Deprecating a block {# greeting/blocks.twig #}**n```twign{% block hey %}n{% deprecated 'The hey block is deprecated, use greet block instead' %}nn{{ block('greet') }}n{% endblock %}nn{% block greet %}nHey you!n{% endblock %}n```nIf we're using this block `{{ block('hey') }}` then:n```nThe hey block is deprecated, use greet block instead (greeting/blocks.twig at line 2).n```nalso other examples come from my mind like deprecating macros, and any other extension point.nnCommitsn-------nn2ab43383 Added deprecated tagn

minor #2870 document support for defining default argument values in the macro tag (olets)This PR was merged into the 1.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nndocument support for defining default argument values in the macro tagnnThe `macro` tag documentation readsnn> Macros differ from native PHP functions in a few ways:n> - Default argument values are defined by using the default filter in the macro bodynnand provides the examplenn```twign{% macro input(name, value, type, size) %}n<input type={{ type|default('text') }} name={{ name }} value={{ value|e }} size={{ size|default(20) }} />n{% endmacro %}n```nnThe implication is that native PHP function-like default argument value definition is not supported.nnv1.12 added support fornn```twign{% macro input1(name, value, type = 'text', size = 20) %}n<input type={{ type }} name={{ name }} value={{ value|e }} size={{ size }} />n{% endmacro %}n```nnThis updates the documentation to cover both ways of defining default argument values.nnCommitsn-------nn40c7553a document support for defining default argument values in the macro tagn

feature #2996 Add filter, map, and reduce filters (fabpot)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.x branch (closes #2996).nnDiscussionn----------nnAdd filter, map, and reduce filtersnnThis PR adds support for 3 new filters: `filter`, `map`, and `reduce`. They take an arrow function as an argument (a PHP closure).nnI have restricted the usage of arrow functions as much as possible as it makes no sense to support them everywhere. So, for now, they are only accepted as arguments to filters (using them as arguments to function is not supported but could be easily added if we have a use case).nnThe syntax is the following: `(x) => x + 3` where `(x)` is the list of arguments, `=>` starts the body, and the body is any Twig expression. Within the arrow function, the context is also available: `(x) => x + offset` works if `offset` is defined in the current context.nn~~These new filters will allow us to deprecate the `if` support on the `for` tag, which does not work well with the `loop` variable:~~nn```twignn{% set sizes = {xs: 34, s: 36, m: 38, l: 40, xl: 42} %}nn{# before #}n{% for name, size in sizes if size < 38 %}n{{ name }} = {{ size }}n{% loop.last ? 'LAST' %} {# <--- works with this PR #}n{% endfor %}nn{# after #}n{% for name, size in sizes|filter(size => size < 38) %}n{{ name }} = {{ size }}n{{ loop.last ? 'LAST' }}n{% endfor %}n```nnThis closes #2785nnCommitsn-------nn5c15f897 added the key to the map and filter filtersn13274bbf added support for iteratorsn175041e0 removed fn in front of arrow functionsndc277635 changed arrow syntaxnb30bce11 added filter, map, and reduce filtersn

Extend opcache check if it is enabledWhen trying to deploy October on shared hosting (www.websupport.sk) I received following error when accessing the frontend pages - ErrorException:> Zend OPcache API is restricted by restrict_api configuration directive.rnBackend was working normally. rnI propose the following change to check not only if the opcache_invalidate exists but also if opcache is enabled.rnThe change was also needed in octobercms files, but to correspond I am also proposing to add it directly to twig.

feature #3108 Add an Intl extension (fabpot)This PR was merged into the 2.x branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnAdd an Intl extensionnnThis new Intl extension is made of 2 parts: one is about formatting dates/currencies/numbers (which is what we already have partially in twig-extensions) and the second part is about ICU data as available in Symfony 4.3+.nnI've decided to put this extension into Twig instead of the Symfony bridge because of the functions that do not rely on Symfony (and I wanted everything in the same place). Also, some Twig features now depends on some external libraries, so it makes more sense now than a few years ago where Twig had no external dependencies. Last, but not least, intl is an important topic, and I think it deserves to be a Twig first class citizen.nnTODO:nn - [x] add documentationn - [ ] what do we want to do with the existing `date` and `number_format` filters?nncloses https://github.com/symfony/symfony/pull/20053ncloses #2567ncloses https://github.com/symfony/symfony/issues/13641ncloses https://github.com/twigphp/Twig-extensions/pull/134ncloses https://github.com/twigphp/Twig-extensions/pull/137ncloses https://github.com/twigphp/Twig-extensions/pull/183ncloses https://github.com/twigphp/Twig-extensions/pull/229ncloses https://github.com/twigphp/Twig-extensions/issues/167ncloses https://github.com/twigphp/Twig-extensions/issues/211nnCommitsn-------nn03d93aac added the Intl extensionn

Fix twig compare

bug #3186 Fix twig compare (dpinheiro)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 3.x branch (closes #3186).nnDiscussionn----------nnFix twig comparennOn twig 2.x the comparison between two variables was being done using the php operators (<, >, <=..), although on 3.x the function `twig_compare` was introduced and it had some issuesnnAs an examplen`'200' > 399` was returning `false` on twig 2.x, but on 3.x it was returning `true`.nnDigging into the code I found out the comparison binaries (`GreaterBinary`, `LessBinary`, etc) were doing the wrong comparison, and the function `twig_compare` was also returning an wrong value if both variables had the same typennNow it's following the convention `-1` if first var is less, 0 if they are equal, or 1 if first var is greaternnThis is my first PR, so please comment if anything is wrongnnCommitsn-------nn0d81c6e5 Fix twig comparen
